 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/usarionmt.showPublicProfile?language=EN>SarionMT</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Master Summoner</span><br>  Posts: 285<br> <font color=#333333>(11/30/01 8:23:22 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=54.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_exclamation_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What is an adequately efficient damage per mana ratio?</span><hr size=1> Well a quick look at Mod Rods here:<br>
<br>
With 3400 mana, I can summon 18 mod rods (spec conjur).  Giving these to a cleric results in a gain of 2700 mana.  However, the loss of 4050hp.  To heal that they'd have to cast 4 CE's on themselves.  This would cost them 1200 mana.  Of course you're not giving it all to one cleric.  So instead you're giving it to lets say 9, 2 each.  They all use a remedy on themselves to heal up the damage.  This costs the cleric mana pool 1575 mana.  So in total you supplied the clerics 1125 mana.  Divided among the nine clerics, 125 mana.  Not even enough for 1 remedy from a single cleric.  Not only that, but they spent time getting/using/healing from the rods that they could have spent medding or healing the tank.  Your other option is to spend you mana nuking and using pets and cutting the fight time.  Personally I try and supply the clerics with a rod prior to the fight so they have the extra just in case, but I'm still full mana for the fight.  Most of the time the clerics don't even use the mod rods anyways.<br>
<br>
As for malosini, its a must.  The importance of slowing the big boys that are quading your tanks with defensive on for close 700's is huge.<br>
<br>
If this post was in response to the two level 60 damage spells in the spell file, they aren't efficient enough for high end mobs.  The efficiency of Sirricco, this is from average damage per hit on high end mobs that accomidate rain spells, is around 4.2, like you said.  That is basicly the same efficiancy as MoE, even if MoE is unresistable. <p>~~
