<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Time is Money:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
It appears to me that the main advantage of Mod Rods is that they speed things up: buffing in preparation for an encounter, recovering between encounters, recovering after a resurrection.  The more valuable time is, the more valuable rods are.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Whose Mana is it anyway?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
A full mana bar is a sin against Karana.  For example, Rangers can heal mod rod damage between fights, assuming they aren't being resurrected.  Rangers get Chloroplast, which so far as I can tell has a very high point healed per mana ratio, and is ideal for recovery periods.  If I am not fighting, exactly what else am I supposed to do with my mana bar?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Shaman Futures Rose Today In Heavy Trading:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
My guild is not uber-large or uber-powerful, and sometimes we are short of a buffing class, like Shaman or Druids.  Mod rods allow me to feed mana to a Druid, who can then buff more people in a shorter amount of time.  Again, some kind of regen buff can be used to heal the damage.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Resistance is Futile--Not!</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Less so since the resistance, but one can find themselves facing an enemy who resists your best efforts to spank them.  Maybe I should give my mana to someone who can put it to better use.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> How much damage IS a Heal worth?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
One common situation is a Main Tank taking all the melee damage while the enemy has Rogues, Rangers and other tanks at their back.  If the Main Tank is not healed, I have noticed that they tend to die rather quickly.  When the main tank dies, bad things happen.  So as a simplification, we can view the Main Tank as a focus item for the Cleric, who pumps mana in, while the other melees pump damage out.<br>
<br>
Based on the numbers supplied by Sarion, one complete heal costs 300 mana to cast, and cures 1000 points of damage, this takes 2 mod rods to generate, ignoring healing the cleric for the moment.<br>
<br>
How much longer can the main tank fight for 1000 points of healing?  I don't know, say 5 stikes at 200 points each.  How much damage do we give the enemy in 5 strikes?  I don't know, how about a dozen tanks can strike 3 times each for 100 points each, yields 12 * 3 * 100 = 3600 damage.<br>
<br>
So in this case, 2 mod rods = 400 mana yields 3600 damage or <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> 9  Damage Per Mana</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.  Way better than Sirroco, and right up there with casting Cadeau on the main tank.<br>
<br>
Of course, the real numbers are likely to be different, but this is not a bad approximation.<br>
<br>
